when it happens (it will happen someday) we see what happens <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 94<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/17/02 2:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> I don't believe that this should be excluded from discussion. Nuclear terrorism is a real possibility and ignoring it will not make it go away. <br>
To answer Zaphod's question, the response would depend on how much could be learned about the perpetrators. It is highly unlikely that terrorists could carry out a nuclear attack without leaving a trail of evidence behind them. This is what happened with the 9-11 terrorists, and a nuclear incident would probably be a great deal more difficult and intricate, with the possibility of detection and tracking, if only after the fact, being that much greater. <br>
A nuclear device leaves traces that can be analyzed. Some of this; the exact composition of the core, for example; could very well lead straight to the point of origin. Intelligence reports, sifted and analyzed with the benefit of hindsight, can often reveal a great deal that wasn't evident beforehand. Again, this happened with the 9-11 attacks. <br>
Would a sovereign government take the chance of detection and launch such an operation? There are some scenarios under which they might, IMO, through error or political inertia. A dictator and his planners may not understand the risk of detection. They may, for example, be misled by earlier assurances from sycophants who cannot then contradict themselves when a nuclear terrorist operation is proposed. For example, suppose that a flunky has told Kim Jong Il, the porn addict and human freak-show who runs North Korea, that their special operations force is airtight and free of American spies. Can this flunky then contradict himself in the face of disaster if Kim suggests using this force for a covert nuclear strike? The flunky's life depends on the reliability of his reports. He has a better chance of getting away with the nuclear strike than he does of surviving a contradiction in his claims to the dictator. <br>
<br>
In any case, once the perps are identified, it will be that identity that shapes the response. Any government that even hints at protecting them, overtly or covertly, would face the kind of consequences the Taliban did, and that other supporters of the 9-11 terrorists should have faced. Any government that had active involvement in the attack would cease to exist. Legal standards of proof aren't necessary in formulating a decision on this, a concept that the peace movement and the associated anti-nuclear movement have done their best to obscure.  <br>
<br>
If it were easy to carry out a nuclear terror attack, it would already have happened. A working nuclear bomb is the holy grail of terrorism, terror groups would spare no effort or expense if they had any chance of pulling it off.<br>
That they haven't succeeded yet suggests the existence of a mitigating factor that is not public knowledge, possibly a revolutionary technical method for detecting fissionable material, or a singularly well-placed network of spies and agents who do nothing else but track nuclear material. <br>
<br>
Some years ago, the CIA ran a sting operation aimed specifically at flushing out the most likely buyers for bootleg nuclear weapons. They gained the cooperation of a sleazy but well-connected Italian arms-dealer, and had him put out the word that there were 3 NATO type fusion bombs for sale at $200M US each (iirc). There were all sorts of authentic sounding business arrangements, requirements for letters of credit, that sort of thing. The prospectus material hinted that the sellers were western military types looking to cash out and disappear. One bona fide buyer jumped at the offer: the government of Iraq. <br>
I have also heard that several foreign intelligence agencies (one from the other side of the Iron Curtain) learned of the deal and tipped off the CIA, not being aware that it was a sting. At least one private citizen, probably a banker, tipped off NATO headquarters in an anonymous letter that had full details of the alleged offer. Italian police, in fact, had enough information to arrest the bogus nuclear gang before buyers appeared. They had to be brought into the plot to keep them from blowing it. This was before the collapse of the Soviet Union. Today, east-west cooperation is much better, and getting better yet, so it is a fair bet that such &quot;merchandise&quot; could not be offered on the open market without intelligence agencies learning about it.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A> at: 12/17/02 2:25:04 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2781<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/1/03 7:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> I've been discussing this for years and warning of its inevitability. Once nukes are going off in capital cities any retaliation would just be revenge. Great for our sense of national pride as we watch them being disintegrated but not an act which will reverse the carnage. I'm not supporting restraint. They should be hit with everything available.<br>
I just think we should concentrate on the customs service reaching a level of efficiency in which fissile material cannot breach national boarders. Also, a home policing force should closely monitor all known sources of fissile material at home and guard it with their lives. This seems like commonsense to me and we should have started implementing it in the 1940's. Policing the World is a ridiculous notion. <br>
Ofcourse this should be discussed. It will be talked of aplenty if it happens and the biggest question being asked will be &quot;Why didn't the Government take action to prevent this?&quot;. Ignoring a problem doesn't make it go away. When I raised this issue repeatedly around the net some years back I was laughed at. Not anymore though. We are lucky Sept 11 wasn't nuclear. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A> at: 1/1/03 7:40:30 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tmayes1999>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 167<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/8/03 4:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> Saddam Huseien In Irauq has a workable A_bomb design<br>
that uses about 35 pound s of Heu. If he gives it to a group like Alkaida, or Hez Bollah, and thy can get Enough Heu,<br>
then nuclear Terrorism would Surely Occurr.Nuclear terrism is a very credible threat. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2848<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/8/03 5:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> I'm surprised it hasn't already happened. I used to give predictions of doom and gloom such as nukes being systematically placed in numerous cities and set off simultaneously. Why? Because thats what I would do. It came as no surprise to me on Sept 11 that several targets were attacked with commercial planes at the same time. The Pentagon, World Trade Centre and quite possibly the White House. We can expect the same kind of organisation with nukes. Everybody assumes that terrorists will be hard pressed to hobble one bomb together. That may be true, but if they do manage to assemble one bomb, then it won't be so difficult to build more. They need only duplicate the first one. After going to the trouble of finding willing scientists, a source of enriched Uranium and a way to smuggle the bomb into a capital city why would they settle for only one device? Mercy? I think not. One bomb would not be enough for them. They want to inflict maximum damage. Sept 11 was a wake up call. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1776<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/8/03 9:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> A terrorist org would probably use a nuke as soon as they possibly could... why risk losing your valuable nuke from detection before you have a chance to use it?  It would probably be NYC or DC as the target.  It would be catastrophic to the US economy... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2854<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/9/03 8:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> Did Al Qaida worry about their trainee pilots being discovered and interrogated? It would have been safer and cheaper to train one pilot. How many were there in total? I haven't a clue but I know it was a lot more than one. <br>
The second a nuke goes off, a national emergency will be declared and the military will take over. Taking out one city won't cripple the US. It will only enrage them. &quot;Wake up a sleeping giant&quot; to steal a phrase. To seriously weaken the US a terrorist organisation would have to destroy 4 or 5 key targets. The Pentagon is one, obviously, but the US would still be on its feet. You would need to take out the main arteries of transportation, communication and leadership. Washington, New York etc. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1784<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/9/03 10:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> The commercial airline attack will never work again.  What passenger in his/her right mind would allow it?  Let's see, terrorists hijack the plane you and 100 other people are on.  You know that you and everyone else is going to die as they kamikazi into another landmark... do you a) remain in your seat and fasten your seat belt and wait for the end? or b) organize an assault on the terrorists because at least you have a chance to survive that?<br>
That's why it had to be done the way it was... near simultaneous attacks.<br>
<br>
Now, this does not equate to a nuclear bomb smuggled into the country, there are no passengers standing by waiting for you to press the button, no one to second guess the predicament they now face and possibly interfere as in the airliner scenario.<br>
<br>
But, the longer a nuke sets idle in someone's basement, the greater the chance it will be discovered prior to detonation.  Use it or lose it will be the terrorists motto. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2869<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/10/03 10:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> There's no certainty of that. They knew the airline tactic wouldn't work again and took full possible advantage of it while customs checks at airports were slovenly. I think it does equate to nuclear weapons. They must realise that the first nuclear attack on America will be the last. After such an attack the US would adapt to make certain it would never be repeated. If possible they would try to inflict as much nuclear carnage as possible. These people are patient. They can wait years until everything is in place to implement maximum nuclear carnage.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sovin>Sovin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tachyon Wrangler</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/1/03 7:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.whitetoweronline.com/hall/icons/Dragon-puter.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> Just been using some idle-time to scroll back through all the &quot;what if's&quot;..extremely interesting, all..and had a thought about this one.<br>
<br>
What if terrorists did manage to procure and place a nuclear bomb (placement/location being a pivotal point of the above discussion)..and managed to place it in the basement of the UN complex (BIG &quot;if&quot;) and detonate it during a full council session..?<br>
<br>
Why assault just one nation when, with a single bomb, you can attack the entire 'world'..? <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.whitetoweronline.com/hall/icons/barth-sig.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sovin>Sovin</A> at: 3/1/03 7:38:07 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 137<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/1/03 11:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> Most terrorists are not out to just cause utter destruction to everything.  They usually have some cause or side.  Destroying the United Nations would surely destroy with it any sympathy for their cause.  However, if you go after a single nation and allies, you are more likely to at least receive some sympathy around the world, sad as it may be.  However, remember, one man's terrorist is another's freedom fighter. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/2/03 12:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> Besides, why would terrorist go after the one organization that, after the various countries of the middle east and europe, grant them political legitimacy? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sovin>Sovin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tachyon Wrangler</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/2/03 1:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.whitetoweronline.com/hall/icons/Dragon-puter.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear threat</span><hr size=1> Now, now..hee..!<br>
